{
  "doc_id": "18282",
  "text": "There have been several reports of pregnancies in patients with tyrosinaemia type II: some have suggested that untreated hypertyrosinaemia may result in fetal neurological abnormalities such as microcephaly, seizures and mental retardation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ; however, other pregnancies have reported normal fetal outcome [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . In view of the uncertainty regarding possible fetal effects of maternal hypertyrosinaemia, dietary control of maternal tyrosine levels during pregnancy is recommended [CITATION_6] .",
